title: For Sale:  Hot Deal on Silencerco Osprey 9mm Suppressor
postcontent:
Silencerco’s Osprey family of pistol suppressors (or silencers, as often called) is a perfect blend of form and function.

With the modern combat handgun in mind, Silencerco set out to create a silencer that performs well and looks like it belongs—the best possible marriage between host weapon and silencer. Silencerco went to work to make a suppressor that maximizes sound suppression levels, allows the use of more host pistols with factory sights, and has more operationally friendly features. What was created was the Osprey pistol silencer available for 9mm, .40 S&W, and 45ACP.
 Although round silencers are very effective for many applications, for a centerfire handgun round it has its limits. To obtain the most suppression, silencers must have as much internal volume as possible; but for a round tubular silencer, the only way to acquire more internal volume is by increasing the overall diameter and/or length. Increasing a tube’s diameter will obscure the site picture of the host gun and inhibit the possibility of holstering a weapon with the silencer still attached to the host gun.
 The Osprey is an eccentric silencer, which means that the bore does not run down the middle of the tube. Because of this eccentric design, most of the baffles and internal volume is beneath the centerline of the bore and out of the way of the gun’s sights, thus leaving the shooter the ability to use factory sights with little or no sight or target obstruction. The Osprey has flat side walls and angled edges that mimic many modern combat handgun slides and is just slightly wider than most host pistols. This feature allows the host weapon to be holstered with many popular open bottom holster designs with Osprey attached. The Osprey contains approximately 30% more internal volume than a traditional round tube silencer at the same length, but does so without obscuring the shooter’s sight picture or adding excessive width and length.

title: For Sale:  KelTec KSG
postcontent:
The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".
This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.
The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil. The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.
Going for well over $900.00 on many of the online forums!

title: For Sale/Trade:  HIGH END PISTON AR PWS MK116 Mod 0 Long Stroke Piston Driven Primary Weapons Systems
postcontent:
For sale is a Primary Weapons System MK116 Mod 0 Complete Upper. 
It utilizes a long-stroke piston system modeled after the ultra-reliable AK-47.
This thing RUNS. Have fired somewhere between 600-700 rounds. Not a single malfunction of any kind, not once. I've fed it everything from quality brass to cheap steel cased Russian stuff like silver bear. it Eats Anything you feed it. It also runs extremely clean, significantly cleaner than DI guns. This is of course due to the design, gases are not kept in contact with the BCG, rather they are pushed into the piston tube. Upper breaks down exactly how a DI upper would, except there is a piston rod attached to the BCG. It is the simplest and most reliable piston AR design out there. All the other piston ARs (I've tried most of them..LWRC Barrett POF LMT Sig etc) operate using short-stroke piston designs which utilize more proprietary parts and result in more metal on metal action, and IMO are more problematic (at least potentially, someday down the road). The other thing I should mention on the topic of other piston guns, is that all the other piston ARs I've tried (while nice) are no where near as light or as well-balanced as the PWS. Most the other piston ARs are front heavy and/or bulky. The PWS is as light as a DI and AS well-balanced as a DI. Weighs in under 7lbs.  Also shoots very flat..the FSC556 muzzle break flash hider is excellent.

Do your research and you'll find not a single bad review on PWS. It is not quite as well known a company as say LWRC, but I believe it is due to marketing, not the quality of builds, b/c PWS has an extremely loyal fan base. I for one am not interested in buying any other rifles outside of the PWS brand. Only selling b/c I'm tight on cash, otherwise I'd keep it. If I didn't have another PWS sitting at home I wouldn't even be selling it regardless of cash needs. You will not be disappointed by this upper I can assure you that.  

Asking $1000 OBO

Would sell the entire rifle (complete upper with complete lower) for $1500 OBO,
but would prefer to keep the lower as it has the best buffer tube system on the market.


Make an offer.

Thanks for looking

title: For Sale/Trade:  HIGH END PISTON AR PWS MK116 Mod 0 Primary Weapons Systems MK 116
postcontent:
For sale is a Primary Weapons System MK116 Mod 0 Complete Upper. 
It utilizes a long-stroke piston system modeled after the ultra-reliable AK-47.
This thing RUNS. Have fired somewhere between 600-700 rounds. Not a single malfunction of any kind, not once. I've fed it everything from quality brass to cheap steel cased Russian stuff like silver bear. it Eats Anything you feed it. It also runs extremely clean, significantly cleaner than DI guns. This is of course due to the design, gases are not kept in contact with the BCG, rather they are pushed into the piston tube. Upper breaks down exactly how a DI upper would, except there is a piston rod attached to the BCG. It is the simplest and most reliable piston AR design out there. All the other piston ARs (I've tried most of them..LWRC Barrett POF LMT Sig etc) operate using short-stroke piston designs which utilize more proprietary parts and result in more metal on metal action, and IMO are more problematic (at least potentially, someday down the road). The other thing I should mention on the topic of other piston guns, is that all the other piston ARs I've tried (while nice) are no where near as light or as well-balanced as the PWS. Most the other piston ARs are front heavy and/or bulky. The PWS is as light as a DI and AS well-balanced as a DI. Weighs in under 7lbs. Also shoots very flat..the FSC556 muzzle break flash hider is excellent.

Do your research and you'll find not a single bad review on PWS. It is not quite as well known a company as say LWRC, but I believe it is due to marketing, not the quality of builds, b/c PWS has an extremely loyal fan base. I for one am not interested in buying any other rifles outside of the PWS brand. Only selling b/c I'm tight on cash, otherwise I'd keep it. If I didn't have another PWS sitting at home I wouldn't even be selling it regardless of cash needs. You will not be disappointed by this upper I can assure you that. 

Asking $1000 OBO

Would sell the entire rifle (complete upper with complete lower) for $1500 OBO,
but would prefer to keep the lower as it has the best buffer tube system on the market.


Make an offer.

Thanks for looking

For sale is one of my 3 identical home protection pieces. This is a Glock 29 with TFO tritium fiber optic sights that fires the very potent 10mm round. What is really surprising is that this Glock hand cannon fires a round that puts a .45 acp round to shame yet is NOT punishing to shoot. I fire 100 rounds of the ammo I plan to use for home defense through each of my home defense pistols, clean them, and then load them and stash them in strategic places in my home. 

For various reasons, I no longer need 3 of these man droppers stashed in my home. No Glock 29 I've ever owned has ever failed to chamber any defense ammo nor failed to fire. Since they certainly are not pretty, they have to be the ultimate in reliable and dependable along with being world class accurate for a compact pistol. I have added Meprolight TFO sights to all of my self protection firearms. The sights are NOT cheap, but they are the brightest sights you can buy for daytime as well as night time shooting. 

This pistol comes Glock box, owners manual and two 10 round magazines that both have the Pierce pinky grip extension. As you can see in the picture, he original Glock copper lube stuff is still on this pistol. If you want a man dropper, and not a pistol that may just possibly dissuade any intruder, this is for you. The night sights are less than 2 years old, so you should get at least 10 more years out of them before they dim.  If you want the pistol without the TFO sights on it, I own the $600 sight pressing machine and can put the original sights back on for $50 less.

The package deal for this home protection system is $525 with all pictured and with the TFO sights. I will need to see proper Indiana ID and preferably a carry permit. This is a fantastic firearm that will last for decades and tens of thousands of rounds. Just ask if you have any questions. Thanks for looking at my ad. If you want to see more pics, just ask. I'm no computer wizard and I kept exceeding the size limit allotted for this ad. Thanks again!
